@page "/components/maskfield"


<DocsPage>
	<MudChip Class="me-n2" Color="Color.Primary">Experimental</MudChip>
    <DocsPageHeader Title="Mask Field" SubTitle="Mask field components are used for input masking."/>
    <DocsPageContent>
		<MudAlert Class="mt-4" Severity="Severity.Error">
            This component is under active development and breaking changes will occur even in minor patch releases.<br/>
            <b>DO NOT</b> use this component if you are not prepared to update your code and adapt to new changes.<br />
            The finished component might not have the same name, might not have the features it has now, or look the same.
        </MudAlert>
        <DocsPageSection>
            <SectionHeader Title="Basic Mask Fields">
                <Description>
					MaskField can accept a certain keypad for each character.
					<br/>
					In this example, you can see the masked and unmasked values along with the key you pressed.
				</Description>
            </SectionHeader>
            <SectionContent FullWidth="true" Outlined="true">
                <MaskFieldBasicExample />
            </SectionContent>
            <SectionSource Code="MaskFieldBasicExample" ShowCode="false" GitHubFolderName="MaskField" />
        </DocsPageSection>

		<DocsPageSection>
            <SectionHeader Title="Control Mask With Mask Parameter">
                <Description>
					<CodeInline>Mask</CodeInline> parameter can be changed dynamically in runtime. New mask will be implement when user focus on Mask Field.
					<br/>
					The default masking characters:
					<br/>
					<CodeInline>a</CodeInline> for letter, <CodeInline>0</CodeInline> for digit, <CodeInline>*</CodeInline> for all characters.
					Also <CodeInline>l</CodeInline> for lowercase and <CodeInline>u</CodeInline> for uppercase letters.
					<br/>
					In this example, you can change the mask with the right text field and see the result on Mask Field.
				</Description>
            </SectionHeader>
            <SectionContent FullWidth="true" Outlined="true">
                <MaskFieldMaskExample />
            </SectionContent>
            <SectionSource Code="MaskFieldMaskExample" ShowCode="false" GitHubFolderName="MaskField" />
        </DocsPageSection>

		<DocsPageSection>
            <SectionHeader Title="Mask With Placeholder">
                <Description>
					By default all mask will be shown on focus. But if Mask Field has placeholder, placeholder will remain until the first value input.
					<br/>
					In this example, you can see the mask field with placeholder example.
				</Description>
            </SectionHeader>
            <SectionContent FullWidth="true" Outlined="true">
                <MaskFieldWithPlaceholderExample />
            </SectionContent>
            <SectionSource Code="MaskFieldWithPlaceholderExample" ShowCode="false" GitHubFolderName="MaskField" />
        </DocsPageSection>

		<DocsPageSection>
            <SectionHeader Title="Change Placeholder Character">
                <Description>
					Placeholder character can be controlled by <CodeInline>PlaceholderCharacter</CodeInline> parameter.
					<br />
					This example shows how to work different placeholder characters with same mask.
				</Description>
            </SectionHeader>
            <SectionContent FullWidth="true" Outlined="true">
                <MaskFieldPlaceholderCharExample />
            </SectionContent>
            <SectionSource Code="MaskFieldPlaceholderCharExample" ShowCode="false" GitHubFolderName="MaskField" />
        </DocsPageSection>

		<DocsPageSection>
            <SectionHeader Title="Change Masking Characters">
                <Description>
					Masking characters can be set in <CodeInline>MaskDefinition</CodeInline> parameter.
					<br/>
					This example demonstrates how to change masking characters.
					<br/>
					Note: <CodeInline>MaskDefinition</CodeInline> cannot be set partially, it overrides the default. Be sure to added all required characters.
				</Description>
            </SectionHeader>
            <SectionContent FullWidth="true" Outlined="true">
                <MaskFieldChangeMaskCharactersExample />
            </SectionContent>
            <SectionSource Code="MaskFieldChangeMaskCharactersExample" ShowCode="false" GitHubFolderName="MaskField" />
        </DocsPageSection>

		<DocsPageSection>
            <SectionHeader Title="Keep Character Positions">
                <Description>
					With <CodeInline>KeepCharacterPositions</CodeInline> parameter, different input approaches supported. By default (false), adding or removing characters forces other characters to move. Otherwise no character move their position.
					<br/>
					In this example, you can see and control the two approaches.
				</Description>
            </SectionHeader>
            <SectionContent FullWidth="true" Outlined="true">
                <MaskFieldKeepIndexExample />
            </SectionContent>
            <SectionSource Code="MaskFieldKeepIndexExample" ShowCode="false" GitHubFolderName="MaskField" />
        </DocsPageSection>

		<DocsPageSection>
            <SectionHeader Title="Add Punctuations to the Value">
                <Description>
					Normally, value contains only user-inputted characters. However, characters that will automatically be added to the value can also be specified in MaskDefinition, <CodeInline>AddToValue</CodeInline> parameter. Once a character set add to value, it can not be used as mask or regex character.
					<br />
					This feature is especially useful when acquiring date value.
					<br/>
					In this example, you can see the two dots are added to the value (if there is at least one inputted character).
				</Description>
            </SectionHeader>
            <SectionContent FullWidth="true" Outlined="true">
                <MaskFieldAddToValueExample />
            </SectionContent>
            <SectionSource Code="MaskFieldAddToValueExample" ShowCode="false" GitHubFolderName="MaskField" />
        </DocsPageSection>

		<DocsPageSection>
            <SectionHeader Title="Regex Masking">
                <Description>
					By <CodeInline>MaskDefinition</CodeInline> Regex masking is also possible with Mask Field.
					<br />
					By default <CodeInline>l</CodeInline> character is used to lowercase and <CodeInline>u</CodeInline> character is used to uppercase characters.
					You can add unlimited Regex definitions as mask character.
					<br/>
					This example demonstrates how to do Regex masking.
				</Description>
            </SectionHeader>
            <SectionContent FullWidth="true" Outlined="true">
                <MaskFieldRegexExample />
            </SectionContent>
            <SectionSource Code="MaskFieldRegexExample" ShowCode="false" GitHubFolderName="MaskField" />
        </DocsPageSection>

    </DocsPageContent>
</DocsPage>
